We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a.) Create an Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory count over the LGU’s Local Road Network which should be done at least once a year; and prepare a Report on the Physical Count of Road Network System and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor;
b.) Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
c.) Direct the General Services Officer-Designate to maintain the Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and their components; and to classification of Barangay, Municipal, Provincial, and National Roads; and
d.) Require the Municipal Accountant to observe the following reporting procedures: i. Prepare the Journal Voucher (JV) to record the beginning balance of the local road network and its components in the general ledger and the Local Road Network Ledger Card, respectively. Support the JV with the Registry of Public Infrastructures for Roads, working paper on the distribution of costs for the road components, and working paper on the determination of the depreciated replacement cost for road components with no available cost per registry; ii. Keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network; and iii. Prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Treasurer to:
a) Stop the practice of using cash advance to pay for the Municipal’s operating expenses and activities, except those that are impractical to be paid in checks;
b) Ensure that the payments for supplies and materials are made through checks and consider establishing a petty cash fund sufficient to pay for petty expenditures of the LGU;
c) Ensure that the purposes of cash advances are on the face of the disbursement vouchers and that are duly supported with complete documents at the time of grant of cash advances;
d) Exercise prudence and install necessary internal control in the utilization of government financial resources to ensure safeguard against unauthorized use and disposition thereof; and
e) Discontinue the practice of granting multiple cash advances to the Municipal Treasurer and any accountable officer and ensure that the previous cash advance has been liquidated before granting additional cash advance.

